Marcellae, being thus honorably recalled and restored in full to all the rights of Roman citizenship, could no longer refuse to comply with the earnest entreaties of his friend Cicero to return to his native land. Accordingly, after some delay, he started upon his homeward journey, but he had proceeded only as far as Athens when he was assassinated by one of his attendants. His body was burned in the Academy, and a marble monument was erected to his memory. ¹
